description: Borrowed from Latin ēdūcere, present active infinitive of ēdūcō (“lead out, raise up”); from ex- (“out, up”) + dūcō (“lead, pull”).

verbs.description: educe (third-person singular simple present educes, present participle educing, simple past and past participle educed)

entries.meaning: (transitive, now rare) To direct the course of (a flow, journey etc.); to lead in a particular direction. [from 15th c.]
(transitive) To infer or deduce (a result, theory etc.) from existing data or premises. [from 16th c.]
(transitive) To draw out or bring forth from some basic or potential state; to elicit, to develop. [from 17th c.]
(transitive, chemistry) To isolate (a substance) from a compound; to extract. [from 17th c.]
(transitive) To cause or generate; to bring about. [from 19th c.]
